Data Analysis Report - employees.csv

Generated: 24/10/2025, 6:11:20 p.m.

Data Source: employees.csv

Record Count: 10

Report Type: standard

Executive Summary

This dataset contains employee information, including name, age, email, salary, hire date, and department, for 10 individuals. It appears to be an HR roster that has undergone an initial data quality check, with numerous fields explicitly marked as invalid.

  • The 'salary' column is almost entirely invalid, with 9 out of 10 records marked as '[INVALID_AMOUNT]' and one containing a negative value.
  • Significant data quality issues are present across multiple columns, including 'age' (2 invalid), 'email' (2 invalid), and 'hire_date' (2 invalid).
  • The consistent use of explicit '[INVALID_...]' markers indicates a prior data cleaning or validation process.
  • No records are fully valid across all fields, as every single entry contains at least one invalid or malformed data point.

Data Quality Assessment

Poor. The pervasive invalidity across critical fields like salary, age, email, and hire date renders most of the data unusable without extensive cleaning and imputation.

Key Insights

Analysis of the dataset reveals the following insights:

  • A significant portion of the dataset (specifically salary, and several age, email, and hire_date fields) is marked as invalid or missing, indicating a fundamental problem with data collection or entry.
  • Every single employee record has an issue with the 'salary' field, either marked as [INVALID_AMOUNT] or containing a negative value, rendering it completely unusable for analysis.
  • Engineering is the most represented department with 4 employees, followed by Sales (3), Marketing (2), and HR (1).
  • A notable number of hires occurred in 2019 and 2020 (6 out of 10 records with valid dates), suggesting recent growth or turnover.

Trends and Patterns

The following trends were identified in the data:

  • There's a consistent pattern of data incompleteness across multiple fields for almost all employees, suggesting systemic issues rather than isolated incidents.
  • Engineering consistently holds the largest share of employees (40%), indicating it might be the largest or a rapidly growing department.
  • The majority of valid hire dates fall within the last two years (2019-2020), showing a trend of recent workforce expansion.
  • Most employees with valid age data are in their late 20s to early 30s (27-35), suggesting a relatively young workforce.

Anomalies and Outliers

The following anomalies were detected:

  • Frank Miller's salary of -5000 is a clear anomaly, as salaries cannot be negative and this is distinct from [INVALID_AMOUNT].
  • David Lee's age being "Unknown" is an anomaly, as other invalid ages are consistently marked as [INVALID_AGE], highlighting an inconsistency in invalid data representation.
  • Frank Miller and Henry Wilson have [INVALID_DATE] for their hire dates, which are critical for tenure analysis and stand out as specific data entry errors.

Recommendations

  • Immediately establish and enforce strict data validation rules at the point of data entry for all HR systems, especially for critical fields like salary, age, email, and hire date, to prevent future invalid entries.
  • Prioritize a comprehensive data audit and remediation of existing employee data to identify and correct all [INVALID_AMOUNT], [INVALID_AGE], [INVALID_EMAIL], [INVALID_DATE], and other inconsistent or erroneous entries.
  • Standardize the representation of invalid or missing data (e.g., always use [INVALID_FIELD] or NULL) to improve data cleanliness and ease of processing.
  • Review HR onboarding and data entry processes to investigate the root causes of these widespread data quality issues, potentially involving training, system improvements, or process changes.
